\par 4. Frequently Asked Questions
\par 
\par Older versions of ignitionServer were a bit easier to use/modify than this current version. This
\par version is MUCH more powerful, has more than enough commands to be useful, and is quite a bit
\par less buggy. Please make sure you read this FAQ before you post to the support tracker.
\par 
\par Q: When I start ignitionServer, nothing comes up!
\par A: It's supposed to do this! ignitionServer now runs as a full-fledged daemon. You will not get
\par    any interface at all (unless you are on Windows NT and you installed the ignitionServer
\par    Monitor). If you are not sure you started it properly, start your IRC client and type:
\par      /server localhost
\par    If you connect to something, the server is running. A less time-intensive method would be to
\par    hit Ctrl-Alt-Del and see if the ignitionServer process is running.
\par 
\par Q: Why doesn't ignitionServer start?
\par A: First, make sure you read the above question. Then, check the following things:
\par    1) Is ircx.conf in the same folder as ignitionServer?
\par    2) Did I modify ircx.conf improperly?
\par    3) Is ircx.conf named properly (it must be ircx.conf -- do not capitalize the extension or any
\par       other part of the name!)?
\par    If you diagnosed those things and still have a problem, make sure ignitionServer isn't running
\par    as another process (Ctrl-Alt-Del). ignitionServer will only start one time. All other times it
\par    will not allow it. 
\par 
\par Q: ignitionServer sends out Closing Link: (AutoKilled: Server Misconfigured) and disconnects users on 
\par     connection
\par A: A new feature was introduced to stop incorrectly configured servers to be used_(E.G. Using Default 
\par     A Lines). To disable this feature simply find X:DIE in ircx.conf file and change the 1 to a 0
\par 
\par Q: What operating system is recommended to run ignitionServer?
\par A: We recommend you use Windows NT 4, Windows 2000, Windows XP, or Windows Server 2003. Windows
\par    95/98/ME is not recommended at all.
\par 
\par Q: Does ignitionServer violate my EULA?
\par A: Probably. We can't answer this for you though. You need to read the End User License Agreement
\par    that came with your operating system. Most versions of Windows and Windows NT only allow 10
\par    simultaneous connections in the EULA. ignitionServer, by design, opens ports and connections
\par    as it needs to. At any one time, ignitionServer can have anywhere from 0 to 65535 connections
\par    open. You take full legal responsibility if you decide to violate your EULA.
\par 
\par Q: Why doesn't MSN connect?
\par A: New versions of ignitionServer do not support the MSN Chat Control. We do not know if or when
\par    this capability will be added.
\par 
\par Q: Is ignitionServer free?
\par A: Absolutely. You should never pay for a copy of ignitionServer because it is released under the
\par    GNU General Public License and is avaliable for download for free from SourceForge.net and our
\par    own website. If you paid for ignitionServer (note: not ignitionServer hosting), we can't help
\par    you get your money back, but we can help prosecute the violator(s). There is one thing I
\par    should note: the GNU General Public License permits people to charge a reproduction fee to
\par    make you a copy. If you only paid for someone to send you a copy, you didn't get ripped off. If
\par    you paid because someone said it costs money (i.e. wasn't free), you did get ripped off :P
\par 
\par Q: How do I add IRC operators?
\par A: Adding operators is a bit harder than before, but the concept is the same as most IRCDs. Browse
\par    to where ignitionServer is installed and open ircx.conf in Notepad. Somewhere in the file, add
\par    an "O" line. It is formatted like this:
\par      O:<hostname>:<password>:<username>:<operator-flags>:<connection-class>
\par    Hostname is the standard IRC hostname of the user (wildcards permitted). For example, if someone
\par    used AOL, their hostname/hostmask would be *@*aol.com. Password and username are
\par    self-explanitory. Operator flags can be any of the following: osixkrRDCcKB. Most are standard
\par    operator flags, however there are a few you should be aware of. R and D allow the oper to
\par    restart and die (stop) the server. They still require the die/restart password.
\par 
